1 Tidy data

1.0.0.1 Learning objectives

  1. Open data sources (Global Burden of Disease & Gapminder)
  2. binding rows and columns across different dataframe

In this chapter, you will learn how to deal with multiple data frames and their shape. Indeed, when we face real-world data it is quite rare that our final data frame is ready to be used right away. We frequently need to combine data from multiple sources and properly shape our data for exploration and analytic purposes.

Here we will use different data sources including the YaoundÃ© data frame that you already know. We will introduce other valuable sources of open-access data for epidemiological research available online. The first is the Global Burden of Disease database available at the following link http://ghdx.healthdata.org/gbd-results-tool. When you open the page you can define the different parameters for your search like location, year, sex, etcâ¦ once you are satisfied you can push the download csv in the bottom right part of the page (see the image below).

This will open a further window (see image below) where you are asked to accept the terms and conditions, decide the kind of download request (it is recommended to select choose the ânameâ or âbothâ options to obtain a proper coding of the variables), and enter your email address. In a few seconds, you will receive the csv by email in a zip folder.

The second data source is the Gapminder datasets available at the following link https://www.gapminder.org/data/. Scrolling down the page you will find a section named âSelect an indicatorâ (see the image below).

For this chapter we will use datasets from the Gapminder âHealth sectionâ.

As you can see the dataframe contains the number of HIV deaths from 1990 to 2011 in sub-Saharan countries. What we have is the full dataframe that Gapminder provides, but what if those data were separated into different files? Here below we will import the same dataframe but split it into 2 parts.

gapminder_hiv_02_03_04_part_1 <- 
  read_csv(file = here("chapter_xxx_tidy_data/data/gapminder_hiv_02_03_04_part_1.csv"), show_col_types = FALSE)

gapminder_hiv_02_03_04_part_2 <- 
  read_csv(file = here("chapter_xxx_tidy_data/data/gapminder_hiv_02_03_04_part_2.csv"), show_col_types = FALSE)

If you explore the dataframes you will see that only the data from the years 2002-2003-2004 are displayed. Furthermore, the first dataframe contains the first 100 rows of our original dataframe, while the second the last 49 rows. This is a simplified scenario of a frequent challenge that you will have to face when working with real-world data. Services like Gapminder or GBD do not always provide you with all the data you need, meaning that you have to combine data from multiple sources. What we have to do here is to bind together the 2 dataframes to have all the data in a single dataframe.

1.2 bind_rows

Now we can proceed. Since our two dataframes contain the same column names we can use the bind_rows() function.

gapminder_hiv_02_03_04 <-
  bind_rows(gapminder_hiv_02_03_04_part_1, gapminder_hiv_02_03_04_part_2)

gapminder_hiv_02_03_04

now our data are bound together. Indeed, what bind_rows() does is simply paste a series of dataframes one below the other. However, the use of this function requires some caution. One important prerequisite is that the names of the columns have to be the same, if not the result will retain all the columns from the two dataframes and will return NA for the length of the dataframe where the column is missing. Letâs see a concrete example.

test_bind_1 <-
  gapminder_hiv_full %>%
  select("country",
         "1999")
test_bind_1 <-
  head(test_bind_1, 100)

test_bind_2 <-
  gapminder_hiv_full %>%
  select("country",
         "2000")
test_bind_2 <-
  head(test_bind_2, 49)

test_bind <-
  bind_rows(test_bind_1, test_bind_2)

in this example we extracted different columns ( â1999â and â2000â) from the Gapminder dataframe and tried to bind together the resulting dataframes. The outcome is that the new dataframe will contain both columns but the first 149 rows in â2000â will contain only NA, while the last 149 rows will be NA in â1999â.

An interesting property of the bind_rows functions is that that the order of the columns name does not matter, meaning that as long as the columns have the same names, the function can automatically match the columns. Letâs check also this case.

test_bind_1 <-
  gapminder_hiv_full %>%
  select("country",
         "1999",
         "2000",
         "2001")
test_bind_1 <-
  head(test_bind_1, 100)

test_bind_2 <-
  gapminder_hiv_full %>%
  select("country",
         "2000",
         "2001",
         "1999")
test_bind_2 <-
  head(test_bind_2, 49)

test_bind <-
  bind_rows(test_bind_1, test_bind_2)

In the example above you can see that, even if the 2 test dataframes have a different columns order, bind_rows() correctly matches the columns (the new order of columns is inherited from the first dataframe inside bind_rows()).

Hint: when using bind_rows(), or in general the functions covered in this chapter is a good practice to double-check if the dimension of the resulting dataframe is the expected one.

1.3 bind_cols

now that we saw how to deal with the dataframe you may wonder how we can do the same with the columns i.e.Â add new columns to a pre-existing dataframe. The function is called bind_cols(). Letâs import the columns for the years â2005â and â2006â

gapminder_hiv_05_06 <- 
  read_csv(file = here("chapter_xxx_tidy_data/data/gapminder_hiv_05_06.csv"), show_col_types = FALSE)
gapminder_hiv_02_03_04_05_06 <-
  bind_cols(gapminder_hiv_02_03_04, gapminder_hiv_05_06) #note that both dataframes contain a column named "country". Columns with the same names will be renamed based on their position

Now the dataframe contains also the columns for the years â2005â and â2006â (and 2 times the column âcountryâ). The bind_cols() function simply adds the columns of the second dataframe to the first one and strictly require the 2 dataframes to be of the same length. Importantly, when you use this function you have to be sure that the 2 dataframes are in the exact same other otherwise the combination will not match the rows.

Given all these limitations, bind_rows() and bind_cols() are the preferred choice only when the dataframes columns are the same (bind_cols()), or they have the exact same number of rows and you are sure that the order is the same (bind_cols()). Most of the time you will have to work with data from different sources and the previous criteria cannot be respected. For these cases, there are mutating join functions that we will cover in the following lessons.
